You have to take the device
away. I'm sorry to tell you

45:26.857 --> 45:30.127 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that, but every parent,
including the Steyer family,
needs to do that, and yours as
well.

45:30.127 --> 45:30.795 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank
you for the advice.

45:30.795 --> 45:32.063 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

45:32.063 --> 45:34.131 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES STEYER: James Steyer,
Common Sense Media.

45:34.131 --> 45:34.865 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Parenting is evolving.

45:34.865 --> 45:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMES STEYER: It sure is.

45:35.733 --> 45:36.267 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you.

45:36.267 --> 45:41.105 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JAMES STEYER: Good
to see you, Judy.

45:41.105 --> 45:47.378 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you.

45:47.378 --> 45:54.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: A poor child who
sorts garbage in Mexico grows up
to become a prominent American

45:54.752 --> 45:57.822 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
writer. How did that happen?

45:57.822 --> 46:02.793 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The new novel "Avenue of
Mysteries" takes us through a
life that includes a host of

46:02.793 --> 46:07.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other vivid characters, events
and places. Its author is
himself a prominent American

46:07.965 --> 46:12.770 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
novelist, John Irving, whose
books include "The World
According to Garp," "Cider House

46:12.770 --> 46:16.474 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Rules," "A Prayer for Owen
Meany," and other bestsellers.

46:16.474 --> 46:19.477 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He joined Jeffrey Brown for our
"NewsHour" Bookshelf
conversation.

46:19.477 --> 46:21.812 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: John
Irving, welcome to you.

46:21.812 --> 46:23.314 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN IRVING, Author, "Avenue
of Mysteries": Thank you.

46:23.314 --> 46:27.485 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, the story of
a writer, he's named Juan Diego,
in your head -- we

46:27.485 --> 46:31.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
meet him old and new. In your
head, did you see him first as
an older man or as a young

46:31.255 --> 46:32.923 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
boy?

46:32.923 --> 46:38.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN IRVING: I saw him first as
a child and an adolescent. I saw
him as a dump kid, an

46:38.963 --> 46:40.698 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
orphan

46:40.698 --> 46:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Literally, a dump
kid, we should say, right? He
works...

46:42.500 --> 46:43.134 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN IRVING: Yes, yes.

46:43.134 --> 46:45.202 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:45.202 --> 46:52.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN IRVING: They're called nino
de la basura, children of the
rubbish. And it's still true

46:52.109 --> 46:57.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
today, as it was in 1970, that
the children are the workers in
the dump who do the sorting

46:57.281 --> 47:00.651 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and separating of the
stuff that's there.

47:00.651 --> 47:07.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And so the
"Avenue of Mysteries is the
specific story of this man, Juan
Diego,

47:07.625 --> 47:11.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but also how -- in a sense,
how we become who we are.

47:11.929 --> 47:14.331 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN IRVING: Yes.

47:14.331 --> 47:23.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It wouldn't be the first time
for me that the focus of a novel
begins at that threshold

47:23.040 --> 47:29.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
age in early adolescence, when
an adolescent is becoming an
adult, or a child is becoming

47:29.113 --> 47:36.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an adolescent. I have always
believed that, in a story, if
something traumatic or
calamitous

47:36.420 --> 47:43.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enough happens to a kid at a
formative age, that will make
him or her the adult they
become.

47:43.294 --> 47:49.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In this case, the
kid, he is the dump -- he works
in a dump, but he picks

47:49.967 --> 47:54.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up books, right? And he learns
to read, he teaches himself to
read, he teaches himself

47:54.105 --> 47:57.208 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
languages.

47:57.208 --> 48:01.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Did that interest you, that sort
of book as a way into a larger
life?

48:01.579 --> 48:10.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN IRVING: Oh, very much. It
was the perfect connection to
the Jesuits' interest in him.

48:10.221 --> 48:17.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Given the high priority the
Jesuits have always put on
education, the fact that there
was

48:17.428 --> 48:25.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a kid who taught himself to
read, the dump reader, they call
him, they were more inclined

48:25.302 --> 48:30.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to think that he could be one of
their children, in their
orphanage, because he was so
teachable

48:30.908 --> 48:33.310 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that he had already
taught himself.

48:33.310 --> 48:36.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There's also -- I
mean, there are many vivid
characters in here; one is

48:36.947 --> 48:44.188 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his sister, Lupe, right, who is
clairvoyant, knows what's on
people's minds. That, of course,

48:44.188 --> 48:49.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allows you to have this mix of
realism, real realism, right, in
the dump, but also a sense

48:49.426 --> 48:50.094 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of magic.

48:50.094 --> 48:53.264 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN IRVING: Yes.

48:53.264 --> 49:02.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is the third time I have
been tempted to bring a
character into a novel who is
partially

49:02.139 --> 49:05.476 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
informed of what I always know.

49:05.476 --> 49:06.644 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

49:06.644 --> 49:10.114 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You're smiling
as you say that, right?

49:10.114 --> 49:19.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN IRVING: Well, because I
always get endings first. I
can't tell you why, but I do.

49:19.356 --> 49:25.462 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is a sense of -- that I
always have as a writer that my
endings are predetermined

49:25.462 --> 49:33.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for me, and this is now the
third time that I have given
some part of that gift -- it's

49:33.337 --> 49:40.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a dubious gift, if you are a
child, especially, and you bear
the burden of it -- giving the

49:40.311 --> 49:50.554 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
character at least the
conviction that he or she knows
what's going to happen.

49:50.554 --> 49:55.226 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's a burden for those
characters, especially if
they're young and innocent in
other ways.

49:55.226 --> 50:03.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, Lupe has -- she has these
two ancestors in earlier novels.
But when a character like

50:03.300 --> 50:11.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that happens to me, a clear
repetition of a character I have
invented before, I'm not

50:11.475 --> 50:18.849 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
even aware of the repetition
until it's too late to turn
back. It's already there.

50:18.849 --> 50:23.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you, the
author, are clairvoyant in that
sense, right? And you have
famously

50:23.053 --> 50:28.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
said you write backwards. You
know the ending of these
stories?

50:28.659 --> 50:36.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN IRVING: I do. I'm not
proselytizing my method. I don't
believe that one writer should

50:36.467 --> 50:41.238 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
tell other writers how to write.

50:41.238 --> 50:48.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just long been my habit,
when I'm thinking about a novel,
when the characters begin to

50:48.279 --> 50:54.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
form, when the story begins to
emerge, I always know more about
the ending, even the aftermath

50:54.585 --> 50:59.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the ending, than I know about
the beginning. And so there's a
construction that works from

50:59.890 --> 51:02.459 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
back to front.

51:02.459 --> 51:08.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't begin a novel until I
have written, not just the last
sentence, but usually, as

51:08.832 --> 51:15.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a result thereof, many of the
surrounding final paragraphs, so
that in addition to knowing

51:15.205 --> 51:20.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what happens, I know what the
voice is. I know how
melancholic, or not. I know how
I

51:20.744 --> 51:25.015 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
sound when I'm telling
the story at the end.

51:25.015 --> 51:29.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This story is
notably about an author in older
age, looking back, filling

51:29.753 --> 51:30.721 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in that story.

51:30.721 --> 51:32.923 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN IRVING: Yes.

51:32.923 --> 51:38.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, the -- I
suppose the requisite question
is about whether you are,
yourself,

51:38.128 --> 51:44.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in retrospective mode, and
thinking about how one becomes
an author, a novelist.

51:44.802 --> 51:52.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN IRVING: I think, in earlier
novels, the main characters who
were writers were exactly

51:52.176 --> 52:00.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as you say. They were an attempt
on my part to understand my own
origins.

52:00.017 --> 52:08.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, in this case, I feel that
because of what happens to Juan
Diego as an older man,

52:08.392 --> 52:15.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he would almost have to be a
writer in order to live as much
in his imagination as he does.

52:15.399 --> 52:24.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't want to say so much that
I give the story away, but I'm
not so sure that -- if

52:24.575 --> 52:30.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this character weren't a fiction
writer, if -- I'm not so sure
that he would get in quite

52:30.681 --> 52:32.049 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as much trouble as he does.

52:32.049 --> 52:32.950 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

52:32.950 --> 52:34.651 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: And
that interested you?

52:34.651 --> 52:37.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN IRVING: It did. It did.

52:37.354 --> 52:46.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm a worst-case scenario
person. I'm only interested in a
story because I kind of go,

52:46.063 --> 52:50.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
